sentences: Felicja Blumental (28 December 1908 – 31 December 1991) was a Polish pianist and composer.
"She was one of the relatively few women born in the first quarter of the twentieth century to have achieved an important career as a concert pianist."
"She was one of the relatively few women born in the first quarter of the twentieth century to have achieved an important career as a concert pianist."
In 1938, she and her husband Markus Mizne moved first to Nice, then to Brazil to escape the growing anti-semitism in Europe.
Her subsequent career saw her settling in Milan in 1962, then in 1973 in London.
Her subsequent career saw her settling in Milan in 1962, then in 1973 in London.

Heitor Villa-Lobos wrote his Piano Concerto No. 5 for her; she was soloist at the world premiere on 8 May 1955, at the Royal Festival Hall, London, with the London Philharmonic Orchestra under Jean Martinon, and she also recorded the concerto in Paris, under the baton of the composer.
Her recording of this work won a Grand Prix du Disque of the Charles Cros Academy of France in 1975.
She died in 1991 in Israel, on one of her many concert tours of the country.
Her daughter, the singer Annette Céline, was one of the organizers of the annual Felicja Blumental International Music festival until her death on 3 June 2017.
